  "prompt": "Which one is correct? 'If it was me' or 'if it were me'?",
  "response": "The correct phrase is **\"If it were me.\"** This is because it uses the **subjunctive mood**, which is used to express hypothetical, unreal, or contrary-to-fact situations. \n\n- **\"If it were me\"** is appropriate when you're talking about a situation that is not true or is purely hypothetical (e.g., \"If it were me, I would have handled it differently.\").\n\nOn the other hand, **\"If it was me\"** is more commonly used in informal speech and is often used in contexts that are not clearly hypothetical or may be factual (e.g., \"I think it was me who left the door open.\").\n\nIn formal writing or when emphasizing a hypothetical situation, \"If it were me\" is the preferred choice.",
